	<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/09/05/morning-agenda-europes-bond-buying-bet/" data-title="Morning Agenda: Europe&#8217;s Bond-Buying Bet" data-description="The European Central Bank will start buying loan-backed bonds. | MetLife plans to fight stricter regulation. | Puerto Rico&#039;s electric power authority has hired a restructuring supervisor. | Defining liquidity for banks.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="round-up">
<div class="ru-top-story">
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">E.C.B. GAMBLES ON BOND-BUYING PROGRAM <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Mario Draghi, the president of the European Central Bank, said on Thursday that the bank would soon start to buy bonds that are backed by loans made to consumers and companies, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/09/04/promise-from-european-central-bank-is-also-a-gamble">DealBookâs Peter Eavis and Alexandra Stevenson write</a></b>. With the move, the central bank is gambling on a complex securities market that for several years has been struggling to get back on its feet. The purchases could make up a substantial share of the roughly 1 trillion euros, or $1.3 trillion, that Mr. Draghi implied that the bank was prepared to spend.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The bond-buying program is aimed at <b>reversing a decline in bank lending</b>, one of the biggest threats to Europeâs economy. The central bankâs plan could help open the credit spigot by freeing up lending capacity at its banks. The plan would work like this: Banks would sell large amounts of loan-backed bonds to the European Central Bank, or into a revived bond market, gaining cash that they could then use to make new loans. And even if the banks donât do large amounts of new lending, selling old loans at good prices could help banks meet any new capital targets that might emerge from the stress tests. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Central bank bond buying can also <b><a HREF="//www.nytimes.com/2014/09/05/business/international/ecb-cuts-interest-rate-further-paving-way-for-more-drastic-measures.html?ref=business">stimulate the system in other ways</a></b>. It lowers interest rates across the system, and it brings new investors into the credit markets, increasing the amount of money available for lending. The program could be a boon for hedge funds and private equity firms that have raised billions of dollars to scoop up distressed assets in Europe. <b>But the plan could also be a flop</b> if, for example, it ends up being too small to make a difference.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">METLIFE TO FIGHT STRICTER REGULATION <span class="divider"> | </span></span> A federal panel voted on Thursday to deem MetLife a âsystemically important financial institution,â thus subjecting it to more intensive regulation than most other life insurers, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/09/04/metlife-is-designated-systemically-important-but-firm-plans-a-fight">Mary Williams Walsh writes in DealBook</a></b>. The American International Group, Prudential Financial and General Electric Capital have already been designated Sifis, or âsystemically important financial institutions.â MetLife indicated on Thursday that it would probably keep fighting inclusion in the group.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Most parts of the insurance industry are regulated by the states, and even the insurers that are designated as systemically important will continue to follow state regulations. The Sifis, however, would be <b>subject to additional oversight by the Federal Reserve</b> and tougher new capital requirements. MetLife now has 30 days to file an administrative appeal to the council; after that, the council will have 30 more days to hold a hearing on MetLifeâs objections. The council then will have 60 more days to make its final decision. If MetLife is still designated as systemically important, the company could bring a lawsuit in federal court.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">PUERTO RICO UTILITY HIRES ADVISER <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Puerto Ricoâs electric power authority, which has been in negotiations with lenders over its debt burden, said on Thursday that it had hired the consulting firm AlixPartners to supervise its restructuring, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/09/04/puerto-rico-said-to-hire-alixpartners-to-lead-restructuring-of-power-authority">DealBookâs Michael J. de la Merced and Michael Corkery write</a></b>. The assignment will be led by Lisa J. Donahue, the head of AlixPartnersâ turnaround and restructuring practice.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The hiring of a chief restructuring officer was part of a deal reached last month between the electric authority, known as Prepa, and its creditors. The authority, which faces a severe cash strain and a mountain of debt, agreed with its lenders to <b>complete a restructuring by next March</b>.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">ITâS JOBS DAY <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Economists expect the unemployment rate to <b>drop to 6.1 percent</b>, from 6.2 percent in July, when the Labor Department releases its August figures at 8:30 a.m. The consensus is for employers to have <b>added 230,000 jobs</b> in August. Average hourly earnings, another closely watched indicator of the labor marketâs health, are expected to increase by 0.2 percent.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">ON THE AGENDA <span class="divider"> | </span></span> In addition to the jobs report, <b>Eric S. Rosengren</b>, president of the Boston Fed, gives a speech to the New Hampshire and Vermont Bankers Associations at 3:45 p.m. in Boston.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">DEFINING LIQUIDITY FOR BANKS <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The rules in effect in 2008 allowed Lehman Brothers to define liquidity rather generously, ultimately leading to its collapse, <b><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/09/05/business/fed-rules-tighten-what-banks-can-count-as-an-asset.html">Floyd Norris writes in the High &#038; Low Finance column</a></b>. At the time, liquidity did not seem that important anyway. Banks could easily borrow against all kinds of assets, taking out loans that had to be renewed again and again. The rules the Federal Reserve approved this week are intended to ensure that banks have <b>enough ready liquidity to survive a crisis of 30 days</b>, which proved not to be the case in the 2008 crisis.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Starting next summer, the biggest banks will have to <b>calculate liquidity daily</b>. Still to come is something called the âNet Stable Funding Ratio,â a sort of one-year liquidity rule, which is supposed to ensure that banks have enough long-term debt that they cannot be driven out of business within a year simply by liquidity pressures. There are also new âleverage ratiosâ to impose minimum levels of capital on banks that have a lot of supposedly very safe assets. âThere has been a lot of activity on the regulatory front, and there is no question that the <b>regulators are a lot more involved</b>, and a lot less trusting, than they were,â Mr. Norris writes. âBut will that be enough?â</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></div>
